**AJAX vs Location.replace**

When it comes to replacing the contents of a page with the contents of a different URL without adding a new page to the navigation stack, both AJAX and `location.replace()` can be used. However, they work in different ways and have different use cases.

### AJAX

AJAX (Asynchronous JavaScript and XML) is a technique for updating parts of a web page without reloading the entire page. It allows you to send and receive data from a server in the background, without interfering with the rest of the page.

To use AJAX to replace the contents of a page with the contents of a different URL, you would typically use the `XMLHttpRequest` object or the `fetch()` API to send a request to the server and retrieve the new content. You would then update the page's content by inserting the new HTML into the page.

Here's a basic example using `XMLHttpRequest`:
```javascript
function replaceContent(url) {
  const xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
  xhr.open('GET', url, true);
  xhr.onload = function() {
    if (xhr.status === 200) {
      const newContent = xhr.responseText;
      document.getElementById('content').innerHTML = newContent;
    }
  };
  xhr.send();
}

